    elia "Floors, not thrones."
    narrator "{i}Her hand finds Elia's arm-brief, warm. The weight of solidarity more than affection. The orbit of two people who've learned to move together through conditions that should tear them apart.{/i}"
    vesper "We can't save everyone. We can save some. That's not nothing."
    elia "It's not enough."
    vesper "It's never enough. That's not an argument against trying."
    narrator "{i}Elia looks at her. Vesper's face in the starlight is composed, certain. The expression of someone who made peace with insufficiency a long time ago.{/i}"
    narrator "Seven years. They've known each other seven years. Stopped counting the impossible situations, the partial victories, the people saved and the people lost."
    narrator "{i}She stands. Moves closer to the viewport. Her reflection ghosts over the stars-transparent, uncertain. Somewhere out there, Pol's pod spins in the dark. Somewhere out there, a mine full of workers is dying slowly enough that the forms call it \"occupational hazard.\"{/i}"
    elia "There's something at that mine. Probably a person. Probably young. And when we find them, they're going to look at us the way Darros did-expecting someone in charge. Expecting to be told what to do."
    vesper "{i}[[standing, meeting her gaze]]{/i} And we're going to show them something different."
    elia "{i}[[quiet]]{/i} Every time we do this, we're being tested. Not by the people we're saving. By the philosophy itself."
    vesper "{i}[[certain, but not harsh]]{/i} That's all we can do. Keep showing up. Keep being wrong and correcting and trying again."
    narrator "{i}The ship hums around them. Drives preparing for the push. Course set for a mining colony called the Kennel, where workers die young and someone found something valuable enough to kill for.{/i}"
    elia "Sixteen hours."
